of animals

693
00:45:42,287 --> 00:45:45,404
that seem to be able to survive
in the darkness

694
00:45:45,687 --> 00:45:50,158
by breaking down the energy
trapped in the whale's bones.

695
00:45:50,447 --> 00:45:54,440
What really fascinates Craig about the
new species discovered on dead whales

696
00:45:54,527 --> 00:45:59,999
is that some are also found in
one other special deep-sea habitat.

697
00:46:07,527 --> 00:46:10,564
Two miles down
along the mid-oceanic ridges,

698
00:46:10,647 --> 00:46:15,323
extraordinary volcanic activity
emerges out of the seabed

699
00:46:15,607 --> 00:46:17,598
in hydrothermal vents.

700
00:46:22,087 --> 00:46:23,600
Scientists were amazed

701
00:46:23,887 --> 00:46:25,878
to discover among these vents

702
00:46:25,967 --> 00:46:28,765
one of the richest oases of life
in the deep ocean.

703
00:46:32,087 --> 00:46:34,078
Since they were first discovered,

704
00:46:34,167 --> 00:46:38,160
a new species has been revealed
every ten days.

705
00:46:38,447 --> 00:46:41,325
And what fascinates Craig
is that some of these species

706
00:46:41,407 --> 00:46:43,523
are exactly the same as those

707
00:46:43,807 --> 00:46:45,798
found on his dead whales.

708
00:46:53,847 --> 00:46:58,443
Remarkably, Craig believes that
his whale skeletons may be providing

709
00:46:58,727 --> 00:47:00,718
vital stepping stones of energy

710
00:47:00,807 --> 00:47:04,004
for larvae journeying
to colonise a new vent.

711
00:47:09,327 --> 00:47:11,318
Like so much in the marine world,

712
00:47:11,407 --> 00:47:14,399
this science is breaking
the frontiers of knowledge

